B. The Presumption of Non-Threat as a Principle of the Liberal Order
The liberal legitimization of the State is traditionally grounded on its fundamentality for the achievement of the triumvirate of “life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness.”161 Other, more progressive versions, advance justice, fairness, and welfare based justifications.162 Common to all these visions is that the individual must be the end of all political action163 and that freedom can only be restricted when its use harms others.164 As we have shown, instrumental arguments against police militarization claim that it adversely affects these basic rights and principles.
Yet we believe that a meaningful liberal order must be based on another foundational principle, one that captures the salient, principled problem of militarized police. To an extent, this foundational principle is derived from the Hobbesian notion of security as a basic end of the commonwealth.165 However, it differs from the basic Hobbesian idea since it does not focus on the individual as a potential victim in the absence of security.166 Nor does our account afford absolute primacy to the concept

