A. Established Democracies in fact have “Hybrid” Militarized Forces
A possible challenge to our theory emanates from the existence of two types of “hybrid” forces.260 The first is the (mainly) Continental European phenomenon of units formally belonging to the military but charged with wide policing duties. The most famous examples of such units are the French National Gendarmerie261 and the Italian Royal Carabinieri,262 or the Spanish Guardia Civil.263 Such forces act as law enforcement agencies, but can also be deployed externally, in some form, during armed conflict.264 They are therefore doubly affiliated with ministries of defense and of interior.265 If established democracies use such forces for public order, does our theory of militarization and exclusion still stand?
